DNS Query Tool

DNS Query Tool is an interactive command-line utility written in Bash that simplifies common DNS lookups using the dig command. Instead of remembering multiple dig flags or command combinations, the script presents a menu-driven interface that allows users to quickly perform specific DNS queries with a single selection.

The tool supports a wide range of DNS record lookups and diagnostics, making it useful for system administrators, network engineers, and developers who frequently troubleshoot DNS issues.

Once launched, the script displays a menu that allows the user to select different query types and enter a domain name. The results are returned directly from dig, often in a shortened format for readability.

The tool supports the following queries:

Full Dig Output – Displays the complete raw DNS response

A Record Lookup – Retrieves IPv4 addresses

AAAA Record Lookup – Retrieves IPv6 addresses

MX Record Lookup – Shows mail server records

NS Record Lookup – Lists authoritative nameservers

TXT Record Lookup – Displays text records such as SPF, DKIM, or verification tokens

CNAME Lookup – Identifies canonical domain aliases

SOA Record Lookup – Shows zone authority information

Reverse DNS Lookup – Resolves an IP address to its hostname

DNS Trace – Displays the full resolution path from root servers to the authoritative server

A built-in DNS propagation check queries several major global resolvers to compare results across networks:

Google DNS (8.8.8.8)

Cloudflare (1.1.1.1)

OpenDNS (208.67.222.222)

Quad9 (9.9.9.9)

This feature allows users to quickly see whether DNS changes have propagated across multiple major DNS providers.

The script also includes usability features such as returning to the main menu if no domain is entered, simple formatted output for propagation checks, and continuous operation through a loop until the user chooses to exit.

Because it relies only on standard Bash utilities and the widely available dig command, the tool runs on most Linux and Unix-like systems without additional dependencies.
